Rapidly increasing cumulative incidence of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) in the EU/EEA and the UK, January 1 to 15 March 2020
The cumulative incidence of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) cases is showing similar trends in EU/EEA countries and the UK confirming that, while in different countries, we are at a different stage of infection, but the COVID-19 pandemic is progressing rapidly in all countries.
Based on the experience from Italy, other countries, hospitals and intensive care units should increase their preparedness for a surge of patients with COVID-19 who need healthcare, and in particular intensive care.
On 31 December 2019, a group of pneumonia cases of unknown cause were reported in Wuhan, Hubei Province, China.
On 9 January 2020, the China Center for Disease Control and Prevention reported the causative agent as a novel coronavirus, named severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
Since then, the illness caused by SARS-CoV-2 infection was referred to as a coronavirus disease (COVID-19).
Evidence obtained so far shows that about 80% of people with COVID-19 have a mild disease, i.e. a respiratory tract infection with or without pneumonia, and most of these recover.
About 14% of cases, COVID-19 is becoming more severe, requiring hospitalisation while 6 percent experience critical illness that require intensive care.
The mortality of patients in the hospital is about 4% due to COVID-19.
In this study, we assess the ongoing trend of the coronavirus outbreak in each EU/EEA country and the UK (Italy) and compare them to Hubei Province.
We also compare the current number of COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the UK, with that in Italy from 31 January to 15 March 2020.
COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the UK
Subsequent to China, COVID-19 was released into more geographically, and the dynamic of this disease is currently taking place in the rest of the world.
On 11 March 2020, the Director General of the World Health Organization (WHO) declared COVID-19 a pandemic.
Spiteri and colleagues in the Eurosurveillance magazine reported the first confirmed COVID-19 cases in Europe according to the WHO definition.
In the EU/EEA, three confirmed cases were reported by France on 24 January 2020, from people who had returned from Wuhan, Hubei Province, China.
On 15 March 2020, COVID-19 cases had been identified in all 30 European/EEA countries and the United Kingdom (UK), whereby from 31 December 2019 to that day, 39,768 confirmed cases and 1,727 deaths were reported, with 17,750 confirmed deaths and 1,441 deaths from Italy alone.
Obtaining cumulative number and cumulative incidence of COVID-19 cases
At the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC), COVID-19 cases in various countries around the world receive only official resources such as the Ministry of Health, the National Health and the World Health Organization and the World Health Organization, being updated every day at 8:00 a.m.
These data were used to assess the trends of COVID-19 in the EU/EEA and the UK, and compare them to the trends of the disease in Italy.
As a indicator of the prevalence of active COVID-19 cases, we calculated the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 in 14 days, followed by the natural course of COVID-19 in EU/EEA countries and the UK, on 1 January to 15 March 2020.
The total number of cases reported from each country on 15 March 2020 was 8:00 a.m. compared with those reported to Italy from 31 January to 15 March 2020.
Trends of COVID-19 in EU/EEA countries and the UK
The 14-day truncated cumulative incidence of COVID-19 in EU/EEA countries and the UK generally follows Hubei Province (China) (Figure 1).
For the EU/EEA and the UK, the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 started to increase around 21 February, and then increased sharply around 28 February 2020 (Supplementary material).
This is mostly driven by the rapid increase in the number of reported cases from Italy, but other EU/EEA countries and the UK showed similar increasing trends of the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 (Supplementary material).
Figure 2 shows the cumulative number of COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the UK compared with that in Italy for a period of 31 January to 15 March 2020.
This figure indicates that on 15 March 8 a.m., the total number of cases reported in 15 other EU/EEA countries and the UK compared with the number of cases in Italy in 3 weeks prior or less.
Our results indicate that the number of notified cases of COVID-19 is rapidly increasing in the EU/EEA and the UK.
The trends in the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 suggest that the pandemic is progressing almost immediately in all countries.
While countries are at different stages of the disease, the response to public health organizations is variable, and there may be different definitions and protocols in countries to choose patients who should be tested for confirmation of COVID-19, including increasing testing speed.
In early March 2020, doctors in affected regions of Italy described a situation in which about 10% of patients with COVID-19 required intensive care and media sources reported that hospitals and intensive care units in these regions had reached their maximum capacity.
Data on admission of COVID-19 cases in a hospital or intensive care unit are currently available at EU/EEA level for only 6% and 1% cases (data not shown).
To complete current surveillance data that focus on the number of cases reported and the number of deaths, this information should be collected in a systematic way.
A study conducted in 112010 found that access to intensive care beds and intermediate care in Europe is very different from 29.2 beds per 100,000 people in Germany to 4.2 beds varies from every 100,000 people in Portugal.
Countries may have fewer or more resources than Italy (12.5 beds) and moderate care for every 100,000 population in 2010.
Modelling scenarios related to healthcare capacity saturation, with expectations for different EU/EEA countries and the UK regarding the prevalence of hospitalised COVID-19 cases associated with over 90% of the capacity of intensive care bed capacity, are provided in the sixth update to rapidly assess the ECDC risk assessment.
Since cases are classified in certain areas of European/EEA countries and the UK, hospitals and intensive care sectors usually serve the population of a region, information about cases and special care beds should preferably be available in the list of domain units for statistics level 2 (NUTS-2).
The experience from Italy and the current trend in other countries show that the COVID-19 pandemic is progressing rapidly in the EU/EEA and the UK.
Therefore, hospitals and intensive care units should prepare themselves for a scenario of sustained transmission of SARS-CoV-2, and an increase in the number of patients with COVID-19 who require healthcare, especially intensive care, such as the case in which Italy is occurring.
As noted in recent rapid ECDC risk assessment, a quick, inclusive, and comprehensive approach to delay the spread of SARS-COV-2 is necessary, with a rapid change from the containment approach to decline, as predicting the rapid increase in the number of cases if not too early, it may cause decision makers and hospitals not have enough time to understand, accept, and adapt their response based on this process.
The rapid risk assessment lists public health measures to mitigate the impact of the pandemic.
There is a short chance for countries to be able to increase their control measures to reduce the spread of SARS-CoV-2 and decrease the pressure on healthcare.
In this case, the lack of success is likely to meet the healthcare system of other EU/EEA countries with a wave of patients who will need special care in the coming days or weeks.
The outbreak of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS-CoV-2), has thus far killed over 3,000 people, infecting 80,000 in China and elsewhere in the world, resulting in catastrophe for humanity.
SARS-CoV-2 is also similar to its own virus, SARS, which caused thousands of people in 2003, and SARS-CoV-2 causes similar symptoms through a similar mechanism.
However, COVID-19 has lower severity and mortality than SARS, but it is more transmissible and affects more elderly individuals than youth and more men than women.
In response to a large number of published content about the emerging disease, this article attempts to provide a timely and comprehensive review of the research that is rapidly expanding.
We will cover the basics about epidemiology, etiology, virology, diagnosis, treatment, prognosis, and prevention of the disease.
Although many questions still need answers, we hope that this review article will help to understand and root out this mysterious disease.
The Spring Festival on January 25, 2020 has become an unprecedented and unforgettable memory to all Chinese who were forced to stay home for all holidays and weeks after the outbreak of the novel viral disease.
The virus is very similar to the coronavirus (CoV) that caused an outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in 2003; thus, it was named SARS-CoV-2 by the World Health Organization (WHO) as well as its associated disease (COVID-19).
The epidemic started in Wuhan, China, and quickly spread throughout the country and to near 50 others all over the world.
As of March 2, 2020, over 80,000 confirmed cases of COVID-19 were reported, with more than 40,000 patients discharged and over 3,000 patients who died.
The World Health Organization warned that COVID-19 is the number of “one people” and potentially more powerful than terrorism.
According to PubMed (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/), since the first report on January 7, 2020 in less than two months, over 200 articles on COVID-19 including virology, epidemiology, pathology, diagnosis, and treatment have been reported to determine the sequence of the virus isolated from the multiple patients.
In this review, we try to collect research progress in this new topic and rapidly developing.
If possible, we will try to compare COVID-19 with SARS and another CoV-caused disease, Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS, an isolated in 2012).
We will also discuss the issues we have learned about taking care of and treating the disease as well as some other necessary questions.
CoVs have been traditionally considered nonlethal pathogens to humans, mainly causing approximately 15% of common colds 4.
However, in this century, we have encountered highly pathogenic human CoVs twice, i.e., SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV, which caused an outbreak in China in 2003 and Saudi Arabia in 2012, and soon spread to many other countries with horrible outbreaks and deaths.
Thus, the current COVID-19 is the third outbreak of the human outbreak in the recorded history of humans.
As shown in Figure 1.1, a cluster of pneumonia cases of unknown origin was reported first on December 31, 2019 from Wuhan to the China National Health Commission.
Seven days later, the sequence of the CoV was released.
On January 15, 2020 the first fatal case from Wuhan was reported.
The epidemic rapidly spread to the cities, provinces, and countries around it.
On January 20, the health care department was reported, and it showed that human-to-human transmission was possible.
On 23 January, the inhabitants of the city of Wuhan were quarantined at a distance, and public transport was stopped.
On January 24, the first clinical study on the disease reported that, out of 41 patients with confirmed cases, only 21 had direct contact with the Wuhan Sea Food Market, which was considered the starting site of the infection from an unknown animal source.
On January 30, the World Health Organization declared the outbreak a global health emergency.
By the time of this report, the disease has spread all over China and near 50 other countries all over the world (Figure 2).
