CoVs are a subfamily of large and enveloped viruses containing a single strand of sense RNA.
These viruses can be divided into four alpha-, beta, gamma, and delta, which are characterized by alpha- and beta-CoVs.
Phylogenetic acid (S) binds to the host angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) and dipeptyl peptidase 4 (DPP4) for SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV, and then membrane fusion occurs.
The RNA genome is released in cytoplasm; after replication of the viral genome, genomic RNA accompanied by glycoproteins and nucleocapsid proteins forms envelope-containing and cytoplasm, which then binds to the plasma membrane to release the virus.
The first genomic sequence of SARS-CoV-2 was reported on January 10, 2020.
By maturing more than 99.8% of the 10 samples collected from the original site of the outbreak, the Huanan Seafood Market in Wuhan, SARS-CoV-2 is a new type of beta-CoV.
SARS-CoV-2 is genetically more similar to SARS-CoV than to MERS-CoV.
Through transmission electron microscopy, SARS-CoV-2 particles were found in ultra-thin sections of human airway envelope.
Human ACE2 was found to be a receptor for SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV.
However, the S protein of SARS-CoV-2 binds to human ACE2 more weakly than SARS-CoV, which is coincident with the fact that SARS-CoV-2 causes less infection than SARS-CoV in patients.
SARS-CoV-2 can also form a novel short protein encoded by orf3b and a secreted protein encoded by orf8.
orf3b in SARS-CoV-2 may play a role in the viral pathogenicity by preventing IFNβ. However, orf8 has no known domain or motif.
On February 18, 2020, Zhou, et al., reported the cryo-EM structure of the human ACE2, with a total length of 2.9 amino acidity in combination with the B0AT1.
They found that the compound, which contained open and closed panels, was combined as a dimer, and that the ACE2-B0AT1 combination could bind two S proteins, which could be evidence for CoV identification and infection.
B0AT1 can become a therapeutic target for drug screening to suppress SARS-CoV-2 infection.
Media and intermediate host
It has been known that both SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV originated from bats and were transmitted to humans via civet cats and camels, respectively.
Through a phylogenetic comparison of SARS-CoV-2 with other CoVs, bats are the native host of SARS-CoV-2 as the new virus is 96% identical to two SARS-like CoVs from bats SL-CoVZX45 and bat SL-CoVZX21.
However, the question that the intermediate host has helped the virus pass through species to infect humans is the response and the transmission route still needs more clarity.
Ji, et al., believe that María, which contains cohesive compounds within the S protein, has worked as a carrier of the virus from bats to humans.
According to a study, researchers in Guangzhou, China, based on 99% genetic similarity to CoVs discovered in pangolins and SARS-CoV-2, say that eating pangolins might be a species of long-term fungal origin that is often used in traditional Chinese medicine - as a potential intermediate host of SARS-CoV-2.
