Cytokine storm has been found to occur before an overreaction of the immune system in patients with SARS and MERS.
Cytokine storm is a form of systemic inflammatory response that features a series of cytokines including TNFα, IL-1β, IL-2, IL-6, IFNα, IFNβ, IFNγ, and MCP-1.
The cytotype refers to immune cells to the release of a large number of free radicals, which are the main cause of ARDS and multicompliant failure.
Repression of the immune system is essential in the treatment of cytokine storms, especially in patients with asthma.
Corticosteroids and tocilizumab, an anti-IL6 monoclonal antibody, has been used to treat cytokine storm.
Other treatments to suppress the immune system in order to prevent the cytokine storm include the module of the immune response guided by T cells; IFN-γ, IL-1 and TNF; JAK inhibition; Blinatumumab; suppressor of sending symptoms of cytope 4 and HDAC inhibitors.
Steroids were widely used as immunosuppressants in the treatment of SARS to reduce the severity of inflammatory damage.
However, using steroids at high dosages was not beneficial in severe lung injury in patients with SARS and COVID-19.
It may also cause severe side effects, especially osteoporosis, and has dramatically adverse effects on improving disease.
However, short courses of corticosteroids at low-to-moderate doses have been recommended to be carefully used for patients with COVID-19 who are in a critical situation.
At the time of writing, no effective antiviral therapy has been approved for the disease.
However, it has been found that intravenous intervention with remdesivir, a nucleotide analog, has been found to be effective in an American patient with COVID-19.
Remdesivir is a new anti-virus drug produced by Gilead initially to treat diseases caused by Ebola and Marlburg viruses.
Subsequent containment of other single-stranded RNA viruses including MERS and SARS viruses was shown by remdesivir.
Based on this, Gilead has sent the compound to China to conduct a series of trials on SARS-CoV-2 infected people, with very promising results.
In addition, baricitinb, interferon-α, leopinavir/ritiron and ribavirin have been suggested as a potential treatment for patients with acute respiratory symptoms.
Diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, liver damage, and other adverse reactions can occur after combined therapy with lipinavir/ritonavir.
Intervention of this treatment with other medications used in patients should be monitored carefully.
Plasma received from recovered patients and production of antibodies
Taking blood from patients who have recovered from a contagious disease to help treat other patients who suffer from similar diseases or to protect healthy people from that disease.
In fact, patients who have recovered often have a relatively large antibody in their blood to cope with diseases.
Antibodies are immunoglobulin (Ig) produced by B lymphocytes to fight diseases and other foreign objects and recognize unique molecules in pathogens and neutralize them directly.
