Coronaviruses (CoVs) belong to the family Coronaviridae, consisting of a group of enveloped, positive-sensed, single-stranded RNA viruses.
These viruses, also called the largest genome of 26 to 32 kilobases among RNA viruses, are Chinese because of the crowned morphology of apopular microscopy.
Structurally, CoVs have integrated genomes that share a similar structure.
Approximately two thirds of genomes include two large rereading frameworks (ORF1a and ORF1b) that are converted into pp1a and pp1ab protein polymers.
The poly protein is further processed and produces 16 non-structural proteins, called nsp1 to 16.
The remaining part of the genome consists of the ORF, which is used for structural proteins such as Spike (S), alpha (E), membrane (M) and nucleoprotein (N).
Several side proteins that are specific were encoded by different lineages of CoVs.
Based on the difference in protein sequences, CoVs are classified into four genera (alpha-CoV, beta-CoV, gamma-CoV and delta-CoV), among which the beta-CoV genera contains most HCoVs and is subdivided into four strains (A, B, C and D).
Phylogenetic evidence has shown that bats and rodents serve as the gene source of alpha-CoVs and beta-CoVs, while birds are the main reservoir of gamma-CoVs and delta-CoVs.
Over thousands of years, CoVs have constantly crossed species barriers, and some have emerged as important factors for human epidemiology.
To date, seven human CoVs (HCoVs) are known.
Among them HCoV-229E and HCoV-NL63 are the common alpha-CoV.
The other five beta-CoVs are HCoV-HKU1, HCoV-OC43, severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus (SARS-CoV), Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) and SARS-CoV-2.
HCoV-229E, HCoV-OC43, HCoV-HKU1 and HCoV-NL6 usually cause mild symptoms, like cold or diarrhea.
In contrast, MERS-CoV, SARS-CoV, and the new SARS-CoV-2 virus are highly pathogenic, causing respiratory tract infections in most patients and potentially causing acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) and emergence of external symptoms.
The first HCoV-229E strain, known as B814, was isolated from the nasal discharge of patients with common cold in the mid-1960s.
Since then, through extensive studies on HCoV-229E and HCoV-OC43, both of which cause self-limiting symptoms have increased our knowledge.
Indeed, the concept was widely accepted that HCoV infection was generally harmless until SARS spread.
The SARS outbreak occurred in 2003, one of the most devastating outbreaks in current time, infected more than 8,000 people, and its raw casualties were approximately 10%.
Ten years later, the Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) outbreak resulted in an outbreak in the Arabian Peninsula spread to other parts of the world.
In 2019, the novel HCoV (2019-nCoV), later renamed SARS-CoV-2, was found to have killed more than 3,120 people and infected more than 91,000 people as of March 2019.
