From: Kadine Maher, Director of the Wikimedia Foundation
To: All Wikimedia Foundation staff
Subject: [Covid-19] Lightening the load and preparing for the future
Upload Date/Time: 14 March 2020, 00:24 UTC
License: CC0: No rights reserved
This month we see ourselves in remarkable circumstances.
The COVID-19 epidemic is something that clearly clears our global interconnection of humans and our responsibilities to one another.
Its challenges are unprecedented for us, but we know that our best response depends on empathy, cooperation, and society that is at the heart of this organization.
The companion and level of care that we have seen among our colleagues through email, call and chat is a sign of incredible humans that we have the chance and honor of working alongside them.
I am very grateful and proud to have you all as a partner.
Last week, someone appreciated what we do.
They reminded me of how magnificent it is that the world can now visit Wikipedia and what a powerful sign that this important source can be online and accessible to all.
Your work makes it possible, whether you keep sites updated or our colleagues earn money or our communities are safe.
The world now needs information that Wikipedia offers more than ever.
This is a moment in which not only what we do but also the way we work will have a meaningful impact on the world.
Because of the importance of this mission and your role in it, we will apply significant modifications from the beginning of the next week in how we do our shared work.
Adjustments to our work and programs
As Robyn mentioned previously, the team-c last night met to discuss our approach and plan for the coming days and months.
During that conversation, we made a decision that we thought was the right answer to what we are facing and the best way to keep the organization sustainable during this time.
We wanted to eliminate stress and support our long-term mission.
If you need to reduce, that’s okay.
To all employees, contractors and contract workers:
Until further notice, we expect 4 hours a day or 20 hours a week to work.
We don’t announce a holiday – if you can work more normal hours, you’ll be in pain with this mission.
However, the world is unpredictable right now, and it doesn’t matter if you care about your loved ones, buy food, or go to your doctor, your health is our priority.
We don’t track your time.
If you are sick, do not work.
This should go without saying, but we say that.
You don’t need to get a emergency leave or a personal leave – just tell your manager and help your group to review calendars and programs and make sure that someone has covered key work.
(If you have tested positive for COVID-19, please let Bryan know of the T&C section so that T&C can help you and make sure your situation is managed properly).
Employees who work for an hour are fully paid.
As we have already said, we adhere to our commitments to contractors and colleagues who work at an hour.
All wages are paid according to the usual hours of work in normal circumstances.
This includes you even if you’re sick and you’re not able to work.
If you want to work, we support you.
Many people use work as a way to drain their stress into the world around us.
What we do, especially in such situations, can be very valuable.
Again, this is about your self-care.
Our desire is to communicate with your manager to know what to expect and to plan accordingly.
Some work is considered essential.
There are things we need to do.
SRE teams, HR Ops, trust and security and attract capital (and others) do critical and important things that may need more support.
We will start a process with other departments to assess current objectives and limit our focus toward supporting the essentials for our mission.
For all of us there is a lot of work, all of us will focus on the most basic projects.
If we do the process right now, we will not be hurt later.
We do not have a plan to work twice as much as we can to finish the pandemic and to handle tasks.
You don’t expect to work extra hours to meet deadlines that are currently impossible.
We accept that conditions have changed and will work to set new targets and timelines if necessary.
How is APP (Annual Planning)?
To match the new reality and expectations of the daily working hour, we intend to adjust our 2021-2020 program timeline.
Our goal is to propose the extension of the 2020-2019 program that gives us more time to budget and allows employees to prioritize critical work, self-care, and care for loved ones, while allowing those who need or wish to work less hours over the next few weeks.
This extension greatly reduces the amount of current workloads throughout the organization.
We will present our proposal to the Board next week and will inform delegates and teams in the next steps as soon as possible.
Thank you for your annual planning team for leadership this.
Office status, exposure to disease and cleaning
Last week, we found that one of the SF-based colleagues may have been exposed to the COVID-19 virus.
However, for more caution, we employed an antiviral cleaning team to disinfect all surfaces in the San Francisco office.
They used an anti-virus solution of a hospital to disinfect all surfaces, as well as for the lobby and elevator that is on our floor.
The building uses its own care protocol and uses products that are useful for the health of its residents.
We are confident that when we decide to go back, the office will be well prepared.
Our Washington office is located in a WeWork, which shares its COVID-19 protocol with us and all the employees based on DBC.
According to the San Francisco State directive, our Washington DC office has become a completely remote set since last week.
As some of our based colleagues know in New York, we have also talked about renting a location in Brooklyn.
These discussions will continue, but they may be delayed.
Some of our colleagues work remotely for the first time.
Older colleagues who work with us remotely know that this can be adaptive and want to recommend you:
Limit the length of meetings to at most one or two hours.
If you need longer sessions, check how they can be held within a few days.
Explain the meeting clearly, have a job order and send the required materials for the study before.
Set the video with tools like Google Docs and Zoom so you can facilitate live collaboration and connection.
Set someone responsible for the session leadership, someone responsible for monitoring chats to follow the questions and list of speakers and someone to note (or share notes).
If you need a comfortable target, send email technical support group.
Use your health allowance for the promise.
Join the #remoties channel in Slack to talk to your colleagues about distributed work.
The Human Resource Operations Team is seeking guidance from the state-based ergonomics to support the increased work divided across the Foundation.
Last week we asked all of the financial points on the basis of the foundation, such as editathon, to cancel public events that are held on budgets and Wikipedia, until the World Health Organization declared the pandemic to be over.
We inform them that we know that our request to cancel programs and other restrictions can make it impossible to do agreed activities related to obtain financial privileges and that no one is punished for delays or modifying their goals.
The next week we will provide more instructions about Wikimania and other topic and regional social integrations.
It seems that public feeling throughout the global community is also uncomfortable because of these disorders and while feeling embarrassed because of their transparency and ability to focus on the activities of their communities, Wikimedia and so on.
As we go ahead, the CRT is trying to create a page on Meta-Wiki to provide a space for society to monitor the impact of the entry and keep our communications with them.
Connecting with COVID-19 matters
For the next Thursday, we will send a meeting invitation for special staff to your calendars at 14:00 UTC with 07:00 time PT.
We use this time and give you more and more information, answer your questions and spend some time connecting with each other.
We are all together in this together and we are here to help you through any possible way.
Meanwhile, you can find relevant information via this email and other COVID-19 related information on Office Wiki.
The CRT has updated these pages and keeps all the information in one place.
We also strive to communicate regularly with those of our employees who live in countries that are currently significantly affected.
If you have questions about travel, events, main work flow or news coverage challenge, or anything else you may need help with, please don’t hesitate to inform and cooperate with the CRT.
We are here to help and support you if necessary.
If you want to talk about a confidential or sensitive topic, please email Bryan Judan - Director of International Human Resources Operations.
None of these changes should be considered as the abandonment of our work and obligations.
Rather, it indicates that at this moment our work and obligations are likely to need to adapt to the way we don’t have in the past.
These are the steps we believe are necessary to support each other so that we can continue to work and support our movement and provide services that the world has to offer.
What we’ve planned will be the time when the Fara is coming, we will be waiting for it.
It’s time to support each other and create space for the important work that will be done in the weeks and potentially months ahead.
We all need you to realize this, so we want you to be your care and your families so that you can be in your best condition when you need it.
Now, please wash your hands and don’t touch your face!
